                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>2. Calculate duration between two times</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>Time Duration</strong> tab finds the difference
                between a start and end time, similar to a timecard calculator.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>start time</strong> and
                  <strong>end time</strong> using the time pickers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If the period crosses midnight (for example, 22:00 to 06:00),
                  check <strong>End time is on the next day</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Calculate duration</strong> to get the elapsed
                  time in several formats.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>3. Convert between HH:MM:SS and decimal hours</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>Time Converter</strong> tab lets you quickly
                convert:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>HH:MM:SS → decimal hours</strong> (useful for payroll
                  and billing).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Decimal hours → HH:MM:SS</strong> (for example, 7.75
                  hours = 7:45:00).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Time calculation formulas</h2>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>1. Convert HH:MM:SS to seconds</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{total seconds} = 3600 \times H + 60 \times M + S \)
                </p>
                <p><strong>2. Convert seconds back to HH:MM:SS</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( H = \left\lfloor \dfrac{\text{seconds}}{3600} \right\rfloor
                  \)<br />
                  \( M = \left\lfloor \dfrac{\text{seconds} - 3600H}{60}
                  \right\rfloor \)<br />
                  \( S = \text{seconds} - 3600H - 60M \)
                </p>
                <p><strong>3. Decimal hours</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{decimal hours} = \dfrac{\text{total seconds}}{3600}
                  \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example: adding work shifts</h3>
              <p>Suppose you worked three shifts:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Shift 1: 7 hours 30 minutes</li>
                <li>Shift 2: 8 hours 15 minutes</li>
                <li>Shift 3: 6 hours 45 minutes</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Convert each to minutes:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Shift 1: \( 7 \times 60 + 30 = 450 \) minutes</li>
                <li>Shift 2: \( 8 \times 60 + 15 = 495 \) minutes</li>
                <li>Shift 3: \( 6 \times 60 + 45 = 405 \) minutes</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Total minutes: \( 450 + 495 + 405 = 1350 \) minutes.</p>
              <p>Convert back to hours and minutes:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Hours: \( \left\lfloor 1350 / 60 \right\rfloor = 22 \) hours
                </li>
                <li>Minutes: \( 1350 - 22 \times 60 = 30 \) minutes</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                So the total is <strong>22:30:00</strong>, or
                <strong>22.5 decimal hours</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Can I subtract times that cross midnight?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. In the <strong>Time Duration</strong> tab, simply check the
                box that says the end time is on the next day. The calculator
                will add 24 hours to the end time before subtracting.
              </p>

              <h3>What are decimal hours used for?</h3>
              <p>
                Decimal hours are commonly used in payroll, billing, and
                timesheets because they make multiplication by hourly rates
                straightforward. For example, 7.75 hours × $20/hour = $155.
              </p>

              <h3>Does the calculator handle negative results?</h3>
              <p>
                In the Add / Subtract mode, if the result would be negative (for
                example, subtracting a larger total from a smaller one), the
                calculator shows a minus sign in front of the HH:MM:SS value.
              </p>
